o  Every city teaches Combat (since you need combat to build troops)
   and Construction (needed to build towers and such -- how a city
   gets built up so it makes sense).
 
o  Each city teaches a regional skill (Beastmastery in plains and
   swamps [I suspect it will still be a much desired skill], Mining in
   mountains, Forestry in forests, and Trading in deserts [how do you
   think they maintain cities in the desert, huh? :->].  Any port
   city will also teach Shipcraft in addition to any regional skill
   indicated by the terrain outside of the city.  The six starting
   safe havens should be divided between all five terrains with the
   last city also being a forest city (basically, 2 Beastmastery, 
   1 Trading, 1 Mining, and 2 Forestry cities). 
 
o  Each city teaches a dark or subversive skill -- either Stealth
   (50%), Persuasion (45%), or Necromancy (5%).  Exactly which of these
   skills a city teaches will remain hidden until discovered by an
   EXPLORE that turns it up.  This will allow for quests to find
   Necromancy.  Safe havens will only have Stealth.  The idea is that
   the underground of each city operates by one of these means and
   you need to find it get get training in it.  Vary the percentages
   to suit your tastes.  
 
o  Each city will teach one magic skill -- Magic, Alchemy, Gatecraft,
   Weather Magic, Scrying, or Artifact Construction.  Since that is
   6 magics, you divide them between the six starting safe havens,
   one each, and then randomly everywhere else.  This will add some
   flavor the the starting selections.
 
Where this differs from your plan is that Shipcraft is an extra and
Forestry isn't guaranteed to starting players.  Magic is just another
Magic and players can pick which magic they might want to start with
by picking their starting city.  Finally, I think that obscuring Stealth,
Persuasion, and Necromancy might add some flavor and hint that these
are potentially troubling skills.  It makes people have to really work
to find them.


